Real life example:

Library Management System 

Requirements:
	Library has books
	Each book has id, title, author
	Users can borrow and return books
	A book can be borrowed by only one user at a time
	System should track who borrowed which book

1. Underline nouns
	Library
	Books
	Users
	System (to borrow or return)

2. For each class, ask what data it must store
	1. Library : 
		books data, users data, system
	2. Books :
		id, title, author, isAvailable
	3. Users :
		id, name
	4. System :
		no attribute as it just perform action (borrow, return and who borrowed which book)

3. For each requirement, who should be repoonsible
	1. borrow and return book -> system
	2. who borrowed which book -> system

Final Classes with attributes and responsibilities

	Library
		- list of books : List<Book>
		- list of users : List<User>
		- System : System

	Book
		- id : int
		- title : String
		- author : String
		- isAvailable : Boolean

		+ Book(int id, String title, String author) : void
		+ markBorrowed(boolean isBorrowed) : void
		+ markReturned(boolean isReturned) : void


	User
		- id : int
		- name : String

		+ User(int id, String name): void

	System 
		- book to user map : Map<int, int>
		- user to book map : Map<int, List<int>> 

		+ borrowBook(int id): void
		+ returnBook(int id): void
		+ handleExchange(id): void  // this will update both maps

--> In the above solution done by me, there are multiple mistakes
	1. classes in UML must be a real life entity. (System is not a real life entity, only User, Book and Library are).
	2. UML should not contain methods like internal implementation (handleExchange is internal implementation).
	3. UML should have single source of truth (maps in System and Book.isAvailable() are depicting same thing related to availability)
	4. Don't use maps, queues, cache, indexes, tables etc. in UML diagram, there are the part of internal implementations

